{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":77611,"duration_api_ms":99345,"num_turns":7,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"ea661dde-004f-4b12-ad4b-1af65f4b95d0","total_cost_usd":0.32623645,"usage":{"input_tokens":6,"cache_creation_input_tokens":24588,"cache_read_input_tokens":146751,"output_tokens":2122,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":24588},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001":{"inputTokens":28,"outputTokens":4342,"cacheReadInputTokens":78567,"cacheCreationInputTokens":13209,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.04610595,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":32000},"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":6,"outputTokens":2122,"cacheReadInputTokens":146751,"cacheCreationInputTokens":24588,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.2801305,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"summary":"All three amendments address real, verified defects. (1) Duration::add panics on overflow — confirmed by compiling and running a test. (2) Process kill only targets the immediate child PID, leaking grandchildren on timeout. (3) Snapshot remains Running during backoff sleep, and resume rejects Running snapshots, creating a stuck-state bug on crash during backoff.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-13-787f9c72","decision":"accept","rationale":"Confirmed by direct test: `Duration::MAX + Duration::from_secs(30)` panics with 'overflow when adding durations'. The Rust std Duration::add calls checked_add().expect(), so it is NOT saturating. Using saturating_add is a trivial, zero-risk fix that eliminates a real panic path. Even though the timeout value is unlikely to be near Duration::MAX in practice, defensive coding at zero cost is the right call."},{"amendment_id":"fr-13-43e2123e","decision":"accept","rationale":"Code inspection confirms force_kill() sends SIGKILL to the immediate child PID only. There is no process group creation (setsid/setpgid) at spawn time and no negative-PID or killpg call at kill time. Any backend that forks (shell wrappers, CLI tools that spawn subprocesses) will leave grandchildren running after timeout, leaking resources. This is a real correctness issue for the timeout contract — 'kill on timeout' must mean killing the entire process tree, not just the top-level child."},{"amendment_id":"fr-13-997cd9b5","decision":"accept","rationale":"Code inspection confirms all three legs of the bug: (1) snapshot is persisted as RunStatus::Running at line 4472-4481 before agent invocation, (2) after a retryable failure, stage_failed is journaled and backoff sleep occurs (up to 60s) with no snapshot update to a resumable state, (3) resume at line 1155-1159 explicitly rejects Running snapshots. If the process crashes during backoff, the project is permanently stuck — it's Running (so resume rejects it) but no process is active. This is a real data-loss / stuck-state bug. The fix should either persist a resumable state (e.g., Paused or RetryPending) before sleeping, or allow resume to recover stale Running snapshots with appropriate staleness detection."}]},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"b26a2764-b82e-4774-a771-599bc0cdd50e"}
